<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="349" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,691,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">Remarks</emphasis>
. The 
<taxonomicName box="[372,562,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Lamprolonchaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[372,562,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">Lamprolonchaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fauna of the Oceania region is not well known. Although McAlpine described some twelve species from the area (
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine, J. F." box="[544,741,727,754]" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" pagination="661 - 700" refId="ref10624" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1964 a) Descriptions of New Lonchaeidae (Diptera). I. The Canadian Entomologist, 96 (4), 661 - 700. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 96661 - 4" type="journal article" year="1964">McAlpine, 1964a</bibRefCitation>
) there have been few further records since that time apart from those from 
<collectingCountry box="[277,316,763,789]" name="Fiji" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">Fiji</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="MacGowan, I." box="[330,537,763,789]" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" pagination="537 - 552" refId="ref10273" refString="MacGowan, I. (2014) The Lonchaeidae of Fiji (Diptera: Schizophora). Zootaxa, 3814 (4), 537 - 552. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3814.4.6" type="journal article" year="2014">MacGowan, 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The original species descriptions by 
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine, J. F." box="[960,1156,763,789]" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" pagination="661 - 700" refId="ref10624" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1964 a) Descriptions of New Lonchaeidae (Diptera). I. The Canadian Entomologist, 96 (4), 661 - 700. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 96661 - 4" type="journal article" year="1964">McAlpine, 1964a</bibRefCitation>
were rather brief and did not include any illustrations of the male genitalia, although it is possible to identify some of the species from drawings made in his PhD thesis (McAlpine, 1962). It is perhaps not surprising that further species are still to be found. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MacGowan" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Lamprolonchaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">L. vila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with its completely black legs is perhaps most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="McAlpine, 1964" authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="1964" box="[831,1140,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Lamprolonchaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ustulata">
<emphasis box="[831,950,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">L. ustulata</emphasis>
McAlpine, 1964
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="McAlpine, 1964" authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="1964" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Lamprolonchaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lustrata">
<emphasis box="[1193,1309,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">L. lustrata</emphasis>
McAlpine, 1964
</taxonomicName>
but as with all 
<taxonomicName box="[377,567,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Lamprolonchaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[377,567,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">Lamprolonchaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species dissection of the male terminalia is required to confirm identification. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MacGowan" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,223,943,969]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Lamprolonchaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vila">
<emphasis box="[151,223,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="349">L. vila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with its distinctive phallus and rather circular exterior lobe of the surstyli is easily distinguished from other members of the genus.
</paragraph>
